problem:
\begin{problem*}{}{}
  Let $a,b,c$ be positive real numbers, such that:
  \[
    a+b+c \geq \frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}
  .\]
  Prove that:
  \[
    a+b+c \geq \frac{3}{a+b+c}+\frac{2}{abc}
  .\]
\end{problem*}

solution:
\begin{soln}
  Note that
  \[
  \frac{a+b+c}{3}
  \ge \frac{3}{\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}}
  \ge \frac{3}{a+b+c}
  .\]

  Therefore,
  \[
    \left( \frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c} \right)^2\ge
    3\left(\frac{1}{ab}+\frac{1}{bc}+\frac{1}{ca}\right)\ge
    \frac{3(a+b+c)}{abc}\ge \frac{3\left( \frac{1}{a}+
    \frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}\right) }{abc}
  .\]

  This gives that
  \[
    \frac{2(
    a+b+c
    )}{3}
    \ge\frac{2\left(
    \frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}
    \right)}{3}
    \ge \frac{2}{abc}
  .\]

  Adding $\frac{a+b+c}{3}\ge \frac{3}{a+b+c}$ and
  $\frac{2(a+b+c)}{3} \ge \frac{2}{abc}$, we get,
  \[
  a+b+c \ge \frac{3}{a+b+c}+\frac{2}{abc}
  .\qedhere\]
\end{soln}
